Your concern is valid. The overall pipeline design is correct (SNS contact point → SQS → Lambda, fixing the message body so `json.loads` works), and the template does loop over `.Alerts` with `range` — so it handles multiple *instances* in one notification. But every label and the description are hard-coded literals, which causes two problems:

1. Contact points are shared in Grafana. The doc says this pattern will be reused for other alerts, but any other rule pointing at `EXAMPLE-PRD-Alerts-SNS-INTERNAL` would report itself as "Airflow High CPU Utilization."
2. Even for this one rule, if several instances fire (e.g., multiple environments), every entry in the array is identical — you can't tell which resource triggered.

The fix is to make the template pull from each alert's own labels/annotations, which Section 7 already requires you to set on the rule anyway:

```
{
  "alerts": [
    {{- range $i, $alert := .Alerts }}
    {{- if $i }},{{ end }}
    {
      "status": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Status }},
      "labels": {
        "alertname": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.alertname }},
        "component": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.component }},
        "account_id": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.account_id }},
        "resource": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.resource }},
        "region": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.region }},
        "stage": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.stage }},
        "subsys": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Labels.subsys }}
      },
      "annotations": {
        "description": {{ printf "%q" $alert.Annotations.description }}
      }
    }
    {{- end }}
  ]
}
```

`printf "%q"` handles JSON escaping (quotes, newlines in descriptions). Two caveats: every rule using this contact point must define all six labels, or those fields render as empty strings; and if a label is missing you won't get an error, just `""`. Also, one testing gotcha worth adding to Section 9: unless the SQS subscription has raw message delivery enabled, SQS receives an SNS envelope with your JSON nested inside the `Message` field as a string — the Lambda needs to unwrap that before `json.loads`.

